It's the exact same punchline.

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:47.440
Having the bad version
of monoamine oxidase gene

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:52.280
does not increase your risk of
antisocial violent behavior.

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:54.540
Having the bad
version of the gene

00:12:54.540 --> 00:12:59.670
and getting brought up in an
environment with abuse vastly

00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:01.020
increased likelihood.

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:03.580
And what they showed in
there was the number of times

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:06.150
of major physical
abuse during childhood,

00:13:06.150 --> 00:13:08.110
the more that was
the case, the more

00:13:08.110 --> 00:13:09.700
there was an interaction here.

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:11.710
Having the good
version growing up

00:13:11.710 --> 00:13:13.640
in a more abusive
setting, yes, it

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:16.210
increases the odds of
antisocial behavior.

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:17.520
Not a big effect, though.

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:18.970
What do we got here?

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:22.030
Yet another gene
environment interaction.

00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:24.970
By now you should be
utterly unwilling to say

00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:27.430
whether any gene
does anything here

00:13:27.430 --> 00:13:30.470
outside the context of saying,
in what sort of setting,

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:31.870
with what sort of background?

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:34.550
Huge interaction here.

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:38.870
So giving a sense here of where
serotonin is fitting into it.

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:42.490
Next piece of neurochemistry
that's relevany-- and this

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:44.210
is not a
neurotransmitter, but this

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:46.150
is a nuerochemical
that occasionally

00:13:46.150 --> 00:13:50.070
gets put into the nervous
system, which is alcohol.

00:13:50.070 --> 00:13:50.660
Alcohol.

00:13:50.660 --> 00:13:54.300
What doe alcohol do
first to neurons on sort

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:55.980
of the nuts and bolts level?

00:13:55.980 --> 00:13:59.930
Is alcohol a mimicker of any
particular neurotransmitter?

00:13:59.930 --> 00:14:00.640
No.

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:03.380
Does alcohol bind to
any particular class

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:05.220
of neurotransmitter receptor?

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:06.760
No, not that either.

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:11.390
Alcohol seems to have some
remarkably nonspecific effects

00:14:11.390 --> 00:14:13.260
in terms of how cells function.

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:16.120
All one could say at
this point is alcohol

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:18.590
is not equal to--
it's kind of working

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:20.580
like this neurotransmitter
or that enzyme

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:22.120
or that-- it's not that clean.

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:25.820
It is a messy drug with lots
of effects in the brain.

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:27.820
So what does alcohol have
to do with aggression?

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:29.390
Everybody knows
the answer to that,

00:14:29.390 --> 00:14:33.100
which is alcohol increases
levels of aggression.

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:34.240
Everybody knows this.

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:35.830
Everybody knows
this and the guy who

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:37.490
gets a couple of
drinks under his built

00:14:37.490 --> 00:14:40.270
and is flinging people out
the bar soon afterward.

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:42.730
Alcohol increases aggression.

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:46.940
What you find, in fact, is there
is no significant relationship

00:14:46.940 --> 00:14:48.000
between the two.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.060
A huge literature
examining this by now.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:55.770
And what you see instead is
one of our if then contingent

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:56.860
themes here.

00:14:56.860 --> 00:15:00.420
Over and over you're getting
this sort of thing coming up.

00:15:00.420 --> 00:15:04.170
Alcohol does not cause
people to be aggressive.

00:15:04.170 --> 00:15:06.780
Alcohol causes
people who already

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:10.140
are aggressive to
become more aggressive.

00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:13.620
Alcohol causes people who
are unaggressive to become

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:14.930
more inhibited.

00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:18.150
What alcohol does
is merely magnify

00:15:18.150 --> 00:15:20.590
the preexisting
social tendencies.

00:15:20.590 --> 00:15:22.070
This theme over and over again.

00:15:22.070 --> 00:15:25.150
That's exactly what testosterone
was doing two days ago.

00:15:25.150 --> 00:15:28.250
Testosterone does not make
number three ranking rhesus

00:15:28.250 --> 00:15:30.700
monkeys start attacking
number two and number one.

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:33.830
It makes them absolutely
torture numbers four and five.

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:36.380
Testosterone does not
create aggression.

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:40.100
It amplifies preexisting social
patterns [INAUDIBLE] that's

00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:43.830
our remove the testosterone
and aggression doesn't go down

00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:44.830
to 0%.

00:15:44.830 --> 00:15:48.620
Interaction with social
history, same exact theme again.

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:50.820
Alcohol does not
cause aggression.

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:53.340
It amplifies
aggressiveness in people

00:15:53.340 --> 00:15:56.660
who already are aggressive.

00:15:56.660 --> 00:15:59.690
Along with that, sort of
as a confounding factor,

00:15:59.690 --> 00:16:02.160
we have this problem that
everybody knows that alcohol

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:03.430
makes you more aggressive.

00:16:03.430 --> 00:16:05.420
And what has also
been shown in studies

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:08.250
is that if you tell
people that you have just

00:16:08.250 --> 00:16:10.160
raised their blood
alcohol levels

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:13.810
infusing in either alcohol
or infusing in saline.

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:16.120
And what you see is
when people believe

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:18.300
their blood alcohol
levels have risen

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:20.070
they become more aggressive.

00:16:20.070 --> 00:16:21.860
What is alcohol about?

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:26.800
Alcohol allows you to give
voice to those preexisting

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:29.400
social tendencies
towards aggression.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:33.090
Modifier over and over
again this sort of theme.

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:35.370
And this has been studied
in all sorts of contexts.

00:16:35.370 --> 00:16:37.370
One really interesting
domain have

00:16:37.370 --> 00:16:39.380
been people who--
anthropologists

00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:42.910
who basically study how
people in different cultures

00:16:42.910 --> 00:16:46.166
learn to get drunk.

00:16:46.166 --> 00:16:47.290
That's kind of interesting.

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:49.706
That must be an interesting
thing to spend your career on.

00:16:49.706 --> 00:16:50.800
What is this about?

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:53.550
Looking at-- one of the
people who does this work,

00:16:53.550 --> 00:16:57.050
looking at this whole issue
of populations that did not

00:16:57.050 --> 00:16:59.230
have a prior history
of heavy alcohol

00:16:59.230 --> 00:17:03.220
use before some explicit
transitional event.

00:17:03.220 --> 00:17:05.450
And what that usually
translates that into

00:17:05.450 --> 00:17:07.540
is Polynesian
islands that did not

00:17:07.540 --> 00:17:10.920
have much alcohol before
they were touched by the West

00:17:10.920 --> 00:17:14.980
during World War II with alcohol
brought in heavily after that.

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:18.270
So the question becomes,
what are people's behaviors

00:17:18.270 --> 00:17:20.319
like in these cultures
as they are first

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:23.440
having a culture of
people drinking to excess?

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:26.210
And the answer is, it depends.

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:29.600
It depends on the people who
are teaching you to drink.

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:31.520
And what you see
is an interaction

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:34.570
between the type
of colonial power

00:17:34.570 --> 00:17:37.640
that controlled the island at
the time and what people did.

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:40.590
And you would see in
British controlled islands,

00:17:40.590 --> 00:17:42.640
American controlled
islands, people

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:44.330
would start
realizing that you're

00:17:44.330 --> 00:17:47.650
supposed to be aggressive and
become more violent when you're

00:17:47.650 --> 00:17:48.370
drunk.

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:51.782
Meanwhile, over in like French
Tahiti, people get drunk

00:17:51.782 --> 00:17:53.240
and they all sleep
with each other.

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:53.740
Aha.

00:17:53.740 --> 00:17:54.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:54.700 --> 00:17:57.780
It's a cultural context
specific sort of thing.

00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:00.770
This shown over and over again.

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:02.830
So a little bit on the
neurochemistry here.

00:18:02.830 --> 00:18:05.370
We then began
working our way left,

00:18:05.370 --> 00:18:08.280
looking first at
hormonal regulation,

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:10.440
the short-term hormonal effects.

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:11.970
Looking at testosterone.

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:14.830
Let's also briefly
go to the other side

00:18:14.830 --> 00:18:18.530
around that time point, the
acute environmental releasers.

00:18:18.530 --> 00:18:21.270
Aggression as our
fixed action pattern.

00:18:21.270 --> 00:18:25.530
What are some of the releasing
stimuli for aggression?

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:29.310
Some of the most reliable ones
are ones that always, always

00:18:29.310 --> 00:18:32.260
demand you to interview an
animal in the same language

00:18:32.260 --> 00:18:36.390
across different species Just as
with sexual behavior releasing

00:18:36.390 --> 00:18:39.970
stimuli, some species become
aggressive in response

00:18:39.970 --> 00:18:45.320
to smells, to sounds, to sights,
to our whole array with this.

00:18:45.320 --> 00:18:46.420
Here's one version.

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:49.860
Here's a species of ant that
gets aggressive in response

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:51.210
to vibration.

00:18:51.210 --> 00:18:53.080
And these are ants
living in East Africa

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:56.440
that have a symbiotic
relationship with trees there

00:18:56.440 --> 00:18:57.840
acacia trees.

00:18:57.840 --> 00:19:01.730
And what happens is the acacia
trees grow these little sort

00:19:01.730 --> 00:19:06.980
of igloo bubbly spheroid
things on their branches, which

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:09.810
have holes in them and
which provide perfect living

00:19:09.810 --> 00:19:11.340
environments for the ants.

00:19:11.340 --> 00:19:13.700
So acacia trees are
giving ants a home.

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:16.840
And what the ants do in return
is they protect the acacia tree

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:18.210
from herbivores.

00:19:18.210 --> 00:19:19.830
Herbivores eating their leaves.

00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:20.650
What happens?

00:19:20.650 --> 00:19:23.150
Along comes a giraffe
and begins to chew

00:19:23.150 --> 00:19:25.580
and it breaks a branch
and the vibration

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:28.390
causes all of these
ants to come pouring out

00:19:28.390 --> 00:19:30.430
and bite the giraffe's lips.

00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:32.820
At which point the giraffe
goes to a different tree.

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:35.500
So we see in that case,
what's the releasing stimulus?

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:37.390
Go and shake a branch
and you suddenly

00:19:37.390 --> 00:19:39.840
have 4,000 ants angry at you.

00:19:39.840 --> 00:19:43.100
All these deals again and
again, interviewing an animal

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:44.470
in its own language.

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:47.980
So what are some of the reliable
releasing stimuli in humans?

00:19:47.980 --> 00:19:50.370
Same theme as with
the sexual behavior.

00:19:50.370 --> 00:19:53.800
We don't have any auditory
stimuli that automatically

00:19:53.800 --> 00:19:54.870
trigger aggression.

00:19:54.870 --> 00:19:56.760
We don't have any
olfactory ones.

00:19:56.760 --> 00:20:00.040
We don't have any-- we've
got some subliminal ones.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:02.720
Remember that study
mentioned a few weeks back.

00:20:02.720 --> 00:20:05.810
Take sweat from someone
who is frightened

00:20:05.810 --> 00:20:07.440
as opposed to the
same amount of sweat

00:20:07.440 --> 00:20:09.820
from someone who's been
happily exercising.

00:20:09.820 --> 00:20:12.520
That was the deal of swabbing
the arm pits of people

00:20:12.520 --> 00:20:14.000
jumping out of airplanes.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.290
Take sweat from someone
who is frightened

00:20:16.290 --> 00:20:20.220
and subliminal exposure to
it, the amygdala activates.

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:22.750
So we're not completely
free of sensory stuff,

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:25.880
but we're not triggered in
any sort of way that's as

00:20:25.880 --> 00:20:27.700
dramatic as in other species.

00:20:27.700 --> 00:20:32.180
So what sort of multi-sensory,
multi-modal sort of things

00:20:32.180 --> 00:20:33.550
trigger aggression?

00:20:33.550 --> 00:20:37.290
Number one, most
reliable one, is pain.

00:20:37.290 --> 00:20:40.500
Make an organism feel
pained and you have greatly

00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:43.470
increased its likelihood of
turning around and biting

00:20:43.470 --> 00:20:45.230
the closest thing to it.

00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:48.210
So pain as a trigger for it.

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:50.560
Frustration as a trigger.

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:51.930
Take a rat.

00:20:51.930 --> 00:20:54.940
Train it to press a lever
10 times, it gets its food.

00:20:54.940 --> 00:20:56.310
10 times, get its food.

00:20:56.310 --> 00:20:57.930
10 times, it doesn't
get its food.

00:20:57.930 --> 00:21:00.210
10 times, you're not
giving it its food.

00:21:00.210 --> 00:21:01.950
Get the rat good and frustrated.

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:03.840
And with great
reliability if there

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:05.500
is another rat
sitting there, it's

00:21:05.500 --> 00:21:07.570
going to spin
around and bite it.

00:21:07.570 --> 00:21:11.460
So displacement aggression,
being driven there

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:14.690
by frustration, by pain,
things of that sort.

00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:19.580
And what's really depressing is
if you were a rat or a primate

00:21:19.580 --> 00:21:22.250
and you were sitting there
being frustrated by not getting

00:21:22.250 --> 00:21:24.760
a reward and your
glucocorticoid levels

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:27.270
have risen, go and
bite somebody else

00:21:27.270 --> 00:21:30.640
and your glucocorticoid
levels will go down.

00:21:30.640 --> 00:21:32.980
And there we describe a
very depressing feature

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:34.330
about our social world.

00:21:34.330 --> 00:21:36.880
Displacing aggression
on somebody else

00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:40.350
in species after species
is stress reducing.

00:21:40.350 --> 00:21:41.480
So triggers.

00:21:41.480 --> 00:21:43.110
Triggers for that.

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:46.630
Great example of this
and a remarkable one,

00:21:46.630 --> 00:21:48.580
back to that business
from a couple of weeks

00:21:48.580 --> 00:21:53.640
ago, that alternative mating
strategy of orangutan males.

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:55.140
That business that
after hearing all

00:21:55.140 --> 00:21:58.700
that heartwarming alternative
strategy stuff of male

00:21:58.700 --> 00:22:01.220
baboons forming
friendships with females.

00:22:01.220 --> 00:22:03.910
Meanwhile, the alternative
strategy with a orangutan

00:22:03.910 --> 00:22:07.000
males being something
that absolutely fits

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:08.850
all the definitions of rape.

00:22:08.850 --> 00:22:10.590
Well, do you see
anything like that

00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:12.540
in some other primate species?

00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:16.620
And you see it every now
and then among male baboons.

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:20.870
Again, defined as
forced sex with a female

00:22:20.870 --> 00:22:22.580
who actively
attempts to get away

00:22:22.580 --> 00:22:24.540
and actively attempts to resist.

00:22:24.540 --> 00:22:27.060
What you see under
that sort of definition

00:22:27.060 --> 00:22:31.330
is every now and then it
will happen in baboons.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:33.050
What is the circumstance?

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:35.070
I've seen it three
times over the years.

00:22:35.070 --> 00:22:37.370
Other people have seen
it occasionally as well.

00:22:37.370 --> 00:22:39.960
It's always the exact
same circumstance.

00:22:39.960 --> 00:22:43.700
It is the number one male
on the day or the day

00:22:43.700 --> 00:22:45.710
after that he has
just been dumped out

00:22:45.710 --> 00:22:47.590
of his alpha position.

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:51.630
And most of the time the animal
goes and mopes somewhere else.

00:22:51.630 --> 00:22:53.650
Most of the time the
animal mopes and then

00:22:53.650 --> 00:22:55.790
finds somebody
smaller to beat up on.

00:22:55.790 --> 00:22:59.170
The only times I've seen this
over all these years, that

00:22:59.170 --> 00:23:01.170
was exactly the circumstance.

00:23:01.170 --> 00:23:04.060
Frustration, aggression
displacement.

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:06.390
Very, very familiar.

00:23:06.390 --> 00:23:09.110
When we get to some more
environmental factors later on,

00:23:09.110 --> 00:23:12.220
some of the big ones, what we
will deal with in this context

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:15.180
is the relationship
between why is it

00:23:15.180 --> 00:23:18.030
that when the economy gets
bad, violence goes up.

00:23:18.030 --> 00:23:20.610
Why does poverty breed violence?

00:23:20.610 --> 00:23:22.330
And this is
consistently the case.

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:24.110
Why is that occurring?

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:26.700
Some framing theoretically
within the context

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:30.130
of frustration and
pain and stress

00:23:30.130 --> 00:23:34.400
are really reliable predictors
of aggressive behavior.

00:23:34.400 --> 00:23:38.060
But again, it's the same
theme as with alcohol.

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:40.760
Pain makes organisms
that are already

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:44.690
predisposed towards being
aggressive more aggressive.

00:23:44.690 --> 00:23:47.810
It does not do so
uniformly across the board.

00:23:47.810 --> 00:23:50.610
Frustration, the
same exact thing.

00:23:50.610 --> 00:23:54.460
Once again, we have something
modulating, amplifying,

00:23:54.460 --> 00:23:57.580
blunting, damping, all
this sort of theme again

00:23:57.580 --> 00:24:00.360
and again, some
other factor there.

00:24:00.360 --> 00:24:01.820
Another example of this.

00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:04.080
Another environmental
trigger-- and study

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:07.806
this subject somewhere in the
1950s or so and the top thing

00:24:07.806 --> 00:24:09.430
that you would get
on the list in terms

00:24:09.430 --> 00:24:12.570
of environmental
releasers for aggression

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:15.270
would be overcrowding.

00:24:15.270 --> 00:24:18.000
This was a whole literature
that emerged at the time.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.380
A psychologist named
Calhoun, John Calhoun,

00:24:20.380 --> 00:24:21.720
started this whole field.

00:24:21.720 --> 00:24:24.260
And what he would do
was take a bunch of rats

00:24:24.260 --> 00:24:28.350
living in an enclosure
of a certain size

00:24:28.350 --> 00:24:30.020
and go about observing them.

00:24:30.020 --> 00:24:32.030
And they're going about
their rat business.

00:24:32.030 --> 00:24:35.250
And now put all of them
into a much smaller space,

00:24:35.250 --> 00:24:37.780
a higher density, crowd them.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:41.370
And what he reported
was aggression explodes

00:24:41.370 --> 00:24:42.010
at that point.

00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:44.050
Aggression goes
through the roof.

00:24:44.050 --> 00:24:45.730
Crowding causing aggression.

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:47.730
The two factoids,
or rather the one

00:24:47.730 --> 00:24:50.790
factoid that everybody
learned from that literature

00:24:50.790 --> 00:24:53.580
for decades afterward from
the Scientific American papers

00:24:53.580 --> 00:24:56.210
was violence would
go up to the point

