00:37:16.940 --> 00:37:20.460
On the average there is a
larger fluctuation in mood,

00:37:20.460 --> 00:37:23.790
affect, when you compare
weekend versus week

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:27.090
day, in particular Friday,
Saturday versus Monday,

00:37:27.090 --> 00:37:27.810
Tuesday.

00:37:27.810 --> 00:37:30.220
Bigger fluctuation
than the mood changes

00:37:30.220 --> 00:37:32.770
you see typically in
women around the time

00:37:32.770 --> 00:37:33.830
of their period.

00:37:33.830 --> 00:37:37.020
So we got some biology here,
but nonetheless there's

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:39.500
other stuff going on as well.

00:37:39.500 --> 00:37:40.860
So what about the biology?

00:37:40.860 --> 00:37:42.440
One thing that
immediately comes up

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:45.730
is this issue that, OK,
perimenstrual periods,

00:37:45.730 --> 00:37:49.800
mood shifts there, are not
purely about aggression

00:37:49.800 --> 00:37:51.320
and irritability.

00:37:51.320 --> 00:37:55.000
They are also about depression
and social withdrawal.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:56.910
That's the time of
cycle when women

00:37:56.910 --> 00:38:00.110
are most likely to have
a depressive episode.

00:38:00.110 --> 00:38:02.660
Very, very different
scenario there.

00:38:02.660 --> 00:38:03.800
So what's up with that?

00:38:03.800 --> 00:38:07.460
You begin to get a hint of
this looking at the baboons.

00:38:07.460 --> 00:38:10.300
What you see is
this is the profile

00:38:10.300 --> 00:38:14.400
you would see in a high
ranking female baboon.

00:38:14.400 --> 00:38:18.640
Look at a low ranking female and
there's no particular change.

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:21.360
Look instead at a
measure of how far

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:23.650
away she stays
from everyone else

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:25.680
and it does something like that.

00:38:25.680 --> 00:38:28.710
In other words, if you are
a low ranking female baboon,

00:38:28.710 --> 00:38:32.050
you don't have the option to
be irritable to somebody else

00:38:32.050 --> 00:38:33.270
and dump on them.

00:38:33.270 --> 00:38:37.400
You instead become more socially
withdrawn, do less grooming.

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:41.300
So an interaction between
place and society, all of that.

00:38:41.300 --> 00:38:43.060
So the biology now.

00:38:43.060 --> 00:38:45.380
Estrogen, progesterone.

00:38:45.380 --> 00:38:48.000
Lots of evidence
that their levels

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.570
and in particular their
ratio is critical to what

00:38:51.570 --> 00:38:52.780
is going on here.

00:38:52.780 --> 00:38:55.010
Massive changes in
the levels of both

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:58.050
of these hormones around
the time of one's period.

00:38:58.050 --> 00:39:00.655
And does not take a
whole lot for the ratios

00:39:00.655 --> 00:39:03.510
thus to become
very, very skewed.

00:39:03.510 --> 00:39:06.130
Back to the advanced
endocrinology stuff,

00:39:06.130 --> 00:39:07.550
the fact that
parts of your brain

00:39:07.550 --> 00:39:08.930
are not just
measuring the levels

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:12.240
of one hormone or another,
but the ratio of the two.

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:14.060
That seems to be pertinent.

00:39:14.060 --> 00:39:16.870
What the evidence
suggests is in one subset

00:39:16.870 --> 00:39:19.900
of women with severe
perimenstrual syndrome--

00:39:19.900 --> 00:39:22.220
and that's about 10%
of the population.

00:39:22.220 --> 00:39:25.190
In one subset of those
individuals what seems to be

00:39:25.190 --> 00:39:29.090
the problem is too much
of a drop of progesterone

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:32.780
around the time of your period.

00:39:32.780 --> 00:39:35.650
So what's the
neurochemistry of that?

00:39:35.650 --> 00:39:37.800
Quick memory from
a few weeks ago.

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:42.162
What's one of the unlikely
things that progesterone does?

00:39:42.162 --> 00:39:44.140
[INAUDIBLE]

00:39:44.140 --> 00:39:44.760
Yeah.

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:46.350
The GABA receptor stuff.

00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:50.450
Progesterone-- by way of often
this metabolite, this sort

00:39:50.450 --> 00:39:52.770
of breakdown product
of it-- progesterone

00:39:52.770 --> 00:39:56.040
being able to bind to
the receptor for GABA

00:39:56.040 --> 00:39:59.280
at a minor tranquilizer
binding site

00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:03.780
just like where benzodiazepines
like Valium bind to.

00:40:03.780 --> 00:40:06.910
Progesterone as
decreasing anxiety,

00:40:06.910 --> 00:40:10.110
progesterone as mildly sedative.

00:40:10.110 --> 00:40:11.940
That's one of the
interpretations that's

00:40:11.940 --> 00:40:13.950
given for what a
more than normally

00:40:13.950 --> 00:40:18.030
rapid drop of progesterone
might have to do with PMS.

00:40:18.030 --> 00:40:20.810
Another subgroup of
women appear to have

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:23.030
an atypically large
drop in levels

00:40:23.030 --> 00:40:28.290
of opioids, endogenous
opioids, around the time here.

00:40:28.290 --> 00:40:31.490
Normally there are
levels of beta endorphin,

00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:35.000
a neurotransmitter slash
hormone with all sorts

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:39.270
of nice effects on mood
and things of that sort.

00:40:39.270 --> 00:40:42.460
And levels tend to go
down around this point.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:46.200
A subset of women with severe
PMS where the marker there

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:49.030
appears to be a
particularly fast drop

00:40:49.030 --> 00:40:52.030
of opioid beta endorphin
levels at the time.

00:40:52.030 --> 00:40:55.390
So just the first bits of
hints of the endocrinology

00:40:55.390 --> 00:40:57.500
of what that is about.

00:40:57.500 --> 00:40:58.900
Final hormones.

00:40:58.900 --> 00:41:03.580
Final hormones, glucocorticoids,
epinephrine, norepinephrine,

00:41:03.580 --> 00:41:05.870
glucocorticoids,
sympathetic nervous system.

00:41:05.870 --> 00:41:09.050
And it's the same exact
deal as two days ago.

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:11.650
Looking at the fact
that those midbrain,

00:41:11.650 --> 00:41:15.117
hindbrain areas get activated
during an aggressive act.

00:41:15.117 --> 00:41:17.200
Oh, does that teach us
something about aggression?

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:18.620
Not in the slightest.

00:41:18.620 --> 00:41:21.350
What you have instead
is the nonspecificity.

00:41:21.350 --> 00:41:24.920
Levels of glucocorticoids
will go up roughly equally

00:41:24.920 --> 00:41:27.830
whether you were running for
your life or running in rage

00:41:27.830 --> 00:41:29.110
or running in joy.

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:32.020
That whole deal again,
sympathetic arousal.

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:33.340
It's nonspecific.

00:41:33.340 --> 00:41:35.960
And back to that sound
byte from two days ago,

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:38.220
the opposite of
love is not hate.

00:41:38.220 --> 00:41:41.250
The opposite of love
is indifference.

00:41:41.250 --> 00:41:45.120
And endocrinologically,
this is the case again.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:48.350
One interesting piece in the
glucocorticoid and sympathetic

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:50.010
nervous system domain.

00:41:50.010 --> 00:41:53.820
Take somebody and poke
their finger with a pin

00:41:53.820 --> 00:41:56.460
or make them physically
uncomfortable

00:41:56.460 --> 00:41:58.960
or something painful
and they activate

00:41:58.960 --> 00:42:03.041
the sympathetic nervous system
as part of their mild stress

00:42:03.041 --> 00:42:03.540
response.

00:42:03.540 --> 00:42:05.140
The early stages of it.

00:42:05.140 --> 00:42:08.920
One class of people where this
doesn't work anywhere near

00:42:08.920 --> 00:42:11.340
as much-- sociopaths.

00:42:11.340 --> 00:42:14.890
And by now a large literature
showing elevated pain

00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:19.260
thresholds in people with
sociopathic violent disorders

00:42:19.260 --> 00:42:21.940
of behavior, elevated
pain thresholds

00:42:21.940 --> 00:42:26.600
and less sympathetic nervous
system responsiveness to pain.

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:29.230
And you should be able to
go off and running with that

00:42:29.230 --> 00:42:32.430
one easily in so far
as metaphorically

00:42:32.430 --> 00:42:36.040
what empathy is about, is
feeling somebody else's pain.

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:39.540
If your own pain system is on
the pretty insensitive side,

00:42:39.540 --> 00:42:41.980
that is certainly going
to have an impact there.

00:42:41.980 --> 00:42:45.010
That's a very
consistent finding.

00:42:45.010 --> 00:42:47.360
So what we are ready for
now is switching over

00:42:47.360 --> 00:42:51.300
to longer term environmental
ideas about aggression.

00:42:51.300 --> 00:42:54.231
Why do I keep pretending
as if the chart is here?

00:42:54.231 --> 00:42:54.730
Here.

